<DocsShell
  title="Bindhub docs"
  description="A compact guide to Bindhub alpha concepts, setup, trust boundaries, and the Loom engine direction."
>
  <h2>What Bindhub is for</h2>
  <p>
    Bindhub is about one feeling: you open another machine and your code folder
    is already there. The public site and docs should help alpha users
    understand that folder continuity promise without making them learn internal
    engine vocabulary first.
  </p>

  <div class="callout">
    <h3>Current alpha frame</h3>
    <p>
      Bindhub Web has a public Astro site and a separate authenticated dashboard
      app. The dashboard uses WorkOS/AuthKit and server-owned API exchange
      boundaries for hosted data modes.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Start here</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      Use <a href="/docs/getting-started/">Getting started</a> for local web app commands
      and alpha setup expectations.
    </li>
    <li>
      Use <a href="/docs/concepts/">Concepts</a> for the Bindhub and Loom vocabulary
      used across the repo.
    </li>
    <li>
      Use <a href="/docs/security/">Security and trust</a> before connecting real
      folders, credentials, or generated files.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Product boundaries</h2>
  <p>
    Bindhub is the product surface. Loom is the source-control and sync engine
    direction underneath it. Git matters because developers use it today, but
    Bindhub treats the shared folder as the user boundary.
  </p>
</DocsShell>
